        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top' nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Zyrixx</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>I think what it comes down to for me(I dont know about others so much), its not so much that the epics effect is completely useless..hey, I wont knock free damage, but the effect really isnt epic. Even for chanters or any other class that has an effect on their epic that is outmatched by a spell in their book. I wont disagree that the damage is nice, it does free up a spell slot, and it is indeed free. The epic itself has some really nice stats as well. But I guess it comes down to the individual and what they think epic means to them. To me, it means the ultimate. It should not only be a symbol of the utmost achievment for a class, but it should also give them the ultimate reward. Now, eventhough its free damage, and it frees a spell slot...is this darkness really the pinnacle of our darkness line? Our level 59 darkness found in our spell book is better than this as far as damage and casting time. You state that Enchanters level 60 speed buffs are better than that of their epic...I wouldnt say their epic sucks, but it certianly should be better than anything they have in their book. </P><P>Im not looking for something so powerful that it allows people to solo dragons or gods. But I think that if they wanted us to have a darkness spell on the epic, it should have been better than anything we have access to. It should have had a quick casting time with a slow recast. It should have its damage almost doubled and it should reduce movement up to maybe 80%. This would be of epic preportions. Since Verant fixed root/snare why would they care if there was a snare spell that reduced movement by this much? Afterall, we can root the mob and stop it completely if we so choose. So there is no imbalance that way. A higher damage per tick and higher damage total wouldnt be unbalancing either. Look at Wizards and their spells. They could lay down 2k+ in a fairly quick amount of time. Having a Necro able to throw out a 2k+ DoT shouldnt be unbalancing toward Wizards, seeing as they deal in Direct Damage, we play with Damage over Time. Ive always thought of Wizard and Necros as cousins. We can both throw out massive damage when we have the chance, only ours takes a bit longer to do full effect. So I really see no reason why an item that is called our epic(to me, supposedly meaning the ultimate item we can gain), couldnt be a little more...well...epic. </P><P>This is why I really cant get excited over this item. The look of the item is a different topic, but I think we could agree that they didnt put too much thought into its design. I probably over reacted a bit and exaggerated by flatly saying it sucks and Necros are minimal damage. Its not all entirely true...but I tend to be a bit attached to the personality I have created and poured my time and my imagination into for almost 2 years. When I feel it slipping away, or being forced to change into something completely different than what he was made to be, I take it personally. Perhaps a bit too personally, but I think most people here can agree, especially if they roleplay their characters at all, its an easy thing to do when it comes to something you have created, molded, and crafted into just what you wish it to be. </P><P>To sum it up for me, I dont think the epic is total junk...the quest itself may be epic and the stats of the item may even be epic, but the effect could have used more oomph to it. The Necro class does not suck totally, I still love playing a dark brooding evil character, but forcing him from being a selfish power mongering controller of the dead, to being a family oriented next door neighbor who shares mana with high elves and gives of himself freely is kinda rough. Maybe I just need a vacation. heh heh</P><P></P><P>Edited by - Zyrixx on 05/05/2001  22:56:18</font></td>
